node.text:
Sometimes it's hard to tell if the galaxy you're looking at is real or a beautifully illustrated artwork of the cosmos...
​
​This real Hubble image shows dwarf galaxy I Zwicky 18 and we're blown away by how beautiful it is. 
​
​I Zwicky 18 is about 59 million light years away from Earth in the constellation Ursa Major. 
​
​Swipe to see what it looks like zoomed out with it's companion galaxy I Zwicky 18 C. 
​
​1️⃣ 📷: NASA, ESA, and A. Aloisi (Space Telescope Science Institute and European Space Agency, Baltimore, Md.)
2️⃣ ​📷: NASA, ESA, Y. Izotov (Main Astronomical Observatory, Kyiv, UA) and T. Thuan (University of Virginia)

node.text:
These birds are outsmarting us at our own bin game! 😱
​
​Australia's sulphur-crested cockatoos (Cacatua galerita) are notoriously clever and endearingly social - now some of these cheeky af scoundrels have learned how to throw open the lids of trash bins to comb through the waste for scraps. What's more researchers have noticed the phenomenon is spreading - the birds are teaching each other how to do this in a form of cultural learning. Smart! 🐦🧠 
​
​Read more at the link in our bio @ScienceAlert. 
​
​📷 Barbara Klump/Max Planck Institute of Animal Behavior

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 26, 2021. May be an image of map.

node.text:
This once was a single stem cell isolated from an embryonic mouse. 🐁 It has cloned and divided itself into several different neural cell types - the special power of stem cells (other cells types can only duplicate themselves).
​
​By using fluorescent markers that differentiate cell types scientists can visually see the outcome of this special type of cellular division - the lineage of that single original cell. 🔬🦠
​
​📷 @societyforneuroscience

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 25, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of 1 person.

node.text:
We know it's hard to believe, but this man was buried 2,400 years ago. ☠️
​
He's called the Tollund Man, and is what's known as a 'bog body' as he was discovered in one of the peaty wetlands. Found in Denmark in 1950, he is so well preserved because of the highly acidic water, low temperature, and a lack of oxygen in bogs. When they pulled him out, authorities initially mistook him for a recent murder victim because of the level of preservation.
​
​Researchers just reanalyzed his stomach content and found out something quite surprising. Check out the link in our bio (@ScienceAlert) to find out more! 
​
​📷: Sven Rosborn/Public Domain

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 24, 2021. May be an image of crustacean.

node.text:
Look! Spiders can be cute! 😍 
​
​This little guy is Menemerus semilimbatus -  a species of jumping spiders. Researchers have just found out that they have a cognitive ability only found in vertebrates. It involved a tiny spider treadmill. Check out the link in our bio for the full story ➡️ @ScienceAlert 
​
​📷: emanuelkern/iNaturalist, CC BY 4.0

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on July 23, 2021.

node.text:
What you're looking at is a piece of wood munched on by shipworms! 
​
​For thousands of years, these 'termites of the sea' have been sinking ships and collapsing wharves with their insatiable appetites. Swipe to see what these little blighters look like. 
​
​New research has discovered that we still don't understand how they digest wood!! Check out the link in our bio for more info ➡️ @ScienceAlert 
​
1️⃣​📷: Rosser1954/Wikimedia Commons/CC BY-SA 3.0
2️⃣​​📷: Borges et al., Center for Materials and Coastal Research

node.text:
Swipe to see which way the slippery yellow slime mold chose to grow! Towards the one or three white discs?
​
​But how does it even know there's a difference when it hasn't been there already and can't see them? This clever microorganisms has a stunning ability to "think" even without a brain, follow the link through our bio (@ScienceAlert) to learn how.
​
​📷 Murugan et al. Advanced Materials, 2021

node.text:
Check out the Milky Way's "yellowballs"! 😄 
​
​They're up to a thousand times the size of our solar system - and in a phase of explosive massive star formation. Volunteers nicknamed them such because of the way the infrared light has been displayed in the Milky Way Project. 
​
​📷 NASA/JPL-Caltech

Wow!! 😮 Check out this rare footage of a glass octopus 🦑 
​
​With incredible powers of transparency only it's eyes, optic nerve and digestive tract remain opaque. This cephalopod, Vitreledonella richardi, was spotted near the remote Phoenix islands. Learn more about it through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷 Schmidt Ocean Institute

node.text:
Our eyes into the far reaches of the universe, the Hubble telescope that has captured many of the stunning space images we share here, has been offline since June 13. NASA finally repaired it with a 'risky' maneuver - read how through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
Pictured here are astronauts Jeffrey A. Hoffman and F. Story Musgrave, performing upgrades on the telescope in space back in 1993.
​
​📷 NASA/JSC
